    "summary": "The Kingdom of Urartu (c. 860–590 BC) was a powerful Iron Age state centered on the Armenian Highlands around Lake Van, that was for over a century the principal rival and northern neighbor of the Neo-Assyrian Empire. Controlling mountainous terrain that gave it natural defensive advantages, Urartu developed sophisticated fortification techniques, irrigation systems, metalworking, and an administrative state that rivaled Assyrian organization. Its capital Tushpa (modern Van) sat on a nearly impregnable cliff above the lake.\n\nAssyrian-Urartu conflict was persistent and intense: multiple Assyrian kings conducted campaigns into the mountains, and Sargon II's famous 8th campaign letter describes a difficult 714 BC expedition against King Rusas I. Urartu was known for its extraordinarily skilled bronze and metalwork — Urartian bronze cauldrons and horse trappings have been found across the ancient Near East and Mediterranean. The kingdom declined in the late 7th century BC under pressure from the Cimmerians (nomadic invaders from the steppe) and Scythians, and was eventually absorbed into the Median Empire. Urartu's cultural legacy continued in the later Armenian kingdoms, which considered themselves heirs to the Urartian tradition.",
